ges/2021/12/articles/main/20230722_wot995.png 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/main/20230722_wot995.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></figure></section><figure> <span itemscope="" itemprop="image" itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject" data-slim="0"><img loading="lazy" src="https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/1873/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png" srcset="https://www.economist.com/img/b/200/293/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png 200w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/300/439/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png 300w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/400/585/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png 400w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/600/878/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png 600w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/640/937/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png 640w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/800/1171/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png 800w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/1000/1463/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png 1000w,https://www.economist.com/img/b/1280/1873/90/sites/default/files/images/2021/12/articles/body/20230722_wof200.png 1280w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 640px, 95vw" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></span></figure><p class="article__body-text">据信<span>苏丹</span>内战已导致至少 300 万人流离失所。这种估计非常不精确，因为可用的信息非常少。当地记者和活动人士遭到围困。</p><p class="article__body-text"><span>然而，一些目击者超出了苏丹交战派系的范围：飞越该国的卫星。来自他们仪器的数据可以提供战争罪的证据，例如烧毁村庄。美国宇航局 (NASA) 运行着一个名为 FIRMS 的卫星系统，该系统可以检测温度异常高的地方。它的目的是追踪森林火灾。今年雨季发生的火灾比过去十年多得多。</span></p><p class="article__body-text"><span>卫星图像证实，21世纪第一次种族灭绝发生地达尔富尔和喀土穆发现的火灾源于暴力。公司检测到大量火灾的地区的高分辨率照片显示建筑物被烧毁。</span></p> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> /内容/phkkqjq2j455o4qf1e279gv5v2r91fj5</guid><link/> https://www.economist.com/espressochart/2023<category>不确定</category><category>联合国</category><category>刚果民主共和国</category><category>埃塞俄比亚</category><category>印度</category><category>尼日利亚</category><category>巴基斯坦</category><category>中国</category><category>人口增长</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Predicting the weather in a warming world]]></title><description><![CDATA[<section class="css-1ugvd2u e1y6i3a60"><style data-emotion="css j1vyw6">.css-j1vyw6 img{display:block;}.css-j1vyw6 .e16qazw92{margin-top:0.25rem;}</style><figure class="css-j1vyw6 e12yhaj20"><img alt="" fetchpriority="high" width="1280" height="720" decoding="async" data-nimg="1" style="color:transparent" sizes="(min-width: 960px) 700px, 95vw" srcset="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=360,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 360w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=384,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 384w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=480,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 480w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=600,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 600w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=834,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 834w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=960,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 960w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1096,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 1096w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1280,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 1280w, https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg 1424w" src="https://www.economist.com/cdn-cgi/image/width=1424,quality=80,format=auto/content-assets/images/20230729_PDP505.jpg" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><style data-emotion="css 18w36g1">.css-18w36g1{width:100%;font-family:var(--ds-type-system-sans);}</style><figcaption class="css-18w36g1 e16qazw92"><style data-emotion="css 11jvxbd">.css-11jvxbd{font-family:var(--ds-type-system-sans-smallcaps);font-size:var(--ds-type-scale--1);font-weight:400;font-variant-ligatures:none;line-height:var(--ds-type-leading-lower);text-transform:lowercase;color:var(--ds-color-london-35);}.e16qazw90+.css-11jvxbd{margin-left:0.5rem;}</style><span class="css-11jvxbd e16qazw91">图片：盖蒂图片社</span></figcaption></figure></section><p class="article__body-text">最近几周，极端高温、洪水和风暴打破了记录，并在世界各地造成了破坏。由于气候变化，诸如此类的反常天气事件将变得更加频繁，但它们异常难以预测。气象学家如何做好准备，应对在变暖的世界中预测天气的巨大挑战？</p><p class="article__body-text">英国雷丁大学的安德鲁·查尔顿-佩雷斯解释了天气预报是如何进行的，以及为什么气象学是一门如此复杂的科学。 <i>《经济学人</i>》的雷切尔·多布斯 (Rachel Dobbs) 调查了预测的下一个前沿领域。她向 Salient Predictions 的首席科学家 Sam Levang 询问人工智能如何在改善天气预测方面发挥作用。 Rachel 还参观了欧洲中期天气预报中心位于意大利博洛尼亚的数据中心，了解如何结合多种技术方法来使天气预报适应 21 世纪的要求。 <i>《经济学人</i>》科技编辑 Alok Jha 担任主持人。时长：43分钟</p><p class="article__body-text"><iframe height="215" src="https://embed.acast.com/theeconomistbabbage/babbage-how-good-can-weather-forecasting-get" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></p><p class="article__body-text">要完全访问<i>《经济学人</i>》的印刷版、数字版和音频版，请在<a href="http://economist.com/podcastoffer/">economics.com/podcastoffer</a>上订阅，并在<a href="http://economist.com/simplyscience/">economics.com/simplyscience</a>上订阅我们的每周科学通讯。</p><p class="article__body-text">收听： <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/babbage-from-the-economist/id508376907">Apple 播客</a>| <a href="https://open.spotify.com/show/0BCUrdrOb3tvfIwazeLBUH?si=nJxIwIpZSp6Yfx6ObmnfhA&amp;dl_branch=1&amp;nd=1">Spotify</a> | <a href="https://podcasts.google.com/feed/aHR0cHM6Ly9yc3MuYWNhc3QuY29tL3RoZWVjb25vbWlzdGJhYmJhZ2U">谷歌</a>|<a href="https://www.stitcher.com/show/the-economist-babbage">缝合器</a>| <a href="https://tunein.com/podcasts/News--Politics-Podcasts/Babbage-from-The-Economis